spanGrp.span: little hare comes, then he says (to) uncle Klaas "I have seen young girls here" (J) "what kind of young girls?"
kom hasietjie, toe sê Oom Klaas, "ng xa nǀaa ng ǃʼoa-ǃʼoa ng ki a", "waffer sort ǃʼoa-ǃʼoa",
kom hasietjie, toe sê (hy vir) Oom Klaas "ek het die jong meide gesien" "waffer sort jong meide"
transcribed by ER in November 2007; checked already many times, but there are still many unclear records; last revision 11.12.2009
cf. Namaseb Hannie Koerant Stories: "The Hyena and the Jackal as suitors of Springbok ladies"
J = Oom Klaas (= jackal = koro), H = hasietjie; OP = Oom Piet (= wolf = brown hyena = gǁain)
/gǃae saa/? /gǃae-sa/? so was wie Herde?? (B: 'die hele klomp'); confirmed in 2009 by B and I
acc to B: /saa/ is NOT 'the springboks come'; this would be [gǃae-saa, hng tsaa] 'die springbokke, hulle kom']
the springbok girls are on the other side (of the dune), oh
die gǃae meide is ander kant, o,
die springbok meide is ander kant, o
/ke xa/ sounds like [tya xa] oder [tye xa]; nice example for TF, B translates as 'EK het hulle gesien'
you (must) take your horse, and I also take my horse, we go in between ...
a ǀai a haasi, ng si ook ǀai ng haasi, ǁʼaa si ng ǀʼee
(jy moet) vat jou perd en ek vat ook my perd, daar loop gaan ons tussen ...
there is no /si/ before /ǁʼaa/, but B repeats it as /si ǁʼaa si ǀʼee/
"you must not ?(sit or be) relaxed, no, make food for us, maake food for us"
"gǀa si ǂxain haʼa, kxʼuua sa aan, kxʼuua sa aan",
"moenie gerus (sit/wees?), nee, maak vir ons kos, maak vir ons kos"
B repeats as /a ǁu ǂxain .../ 'jy moenie gerus wees/sit'; the beginning is probably not a fully grammatical clause here
(...) remeains unclear; sounds like [(h)oo ha]; B repeats either /tcoo-a/ 'sit' or nothing at all!
H says to J "why do you sit around here, make food for us", so that they can eat before they go to the springbok girls
they make food, they make food, they eat, they wash, they wash, they wash, they wash, they comb, comb, comb, comb, comb
hng kxʼuu aan, hng kxʼuu aan, hng aan, hng ǁʼali, hng ǁʼali, hng ǁʼali, hng ǁʼali, hng kama, kama, kama, kama, kama,
hulle maak kos, hulle maak kos, hulle eet, hulle was, hulle was, hulle was, hulle was, hulle kam, kam, kam, kam, kam
(J) "nou, little rabbit, I want to put on my clothes", (H) "no, don't get dressed, you shall go and get dressed on the dune"
"nou, nǃaun ʘoang, ng ǂao ng nǁaa ng ǃxaike", "haʼa, xuua ǁhaa, a si ǁʼae ng nǁaa ng nǃoon",
"nou hasietjie, ek wil (eers) my klere aantrek", "nee, los die aantrek, jy sal loop aantrek op die duin"
/ʘoa/ sounds like [koang] or [kuang]; B's bilabial click often very weak
you have given me a plan, I go and get dressed on the dune"
nee, a xa tsaa nya plana, ng ǁʼng nǁaa ng nǃoon",
jy het vir my 'n plan gegee, (lat) ek loop trek aan op die duin"
both B and I repeat /ǁʼng/ and did not accept my /ǁʼae ng/; why? not 100% convinced, should be re-checked
(H) "you (shall) go and see the springbok girls, the springbok girls are here, springboks, springboks"
"[gǀa] ǁʼae ng nǀaa gǃae meide, gǃae meide ke nǁaa ki gǃae, gǃae,
"jy sal loop sien die sprongbokmeide, die springbokmeide bly hierso, springbokke, springbokke"
beginning unclear, probably a speech error; sounds like /gǀa/, but it is either repeated just as /a/ 2SG, or as /nǀa a/ 'lat jy kan loop sien'
now /ǁʼae ng/ was sueddnly OK again
they are beautiful, they are beautiful, they ?, they ?, hm
hng ǀhaqoka, hng ǀhaqoka, [hng] hng (...), hng (...), hm",
hulle is mooi, hulle is mooi, hulle ?, hulle ?, hm
(...) was first given as /kere/ 'blits', later as /kaqle(ke)/ and translated as 'white stripes in a springbok face'; I don't know what it 'correct' here
(he) takes his clothes, he puts (them) into a sack
[ǁa] ǀai ha ǃxaike, ha ǀʼee ng gǃuu,
(hy) sit sy klere in die velsak
beginning unclear; probably again a speech error, it should just be /ha ǀai/
when (he) has put (them) in the sack, (he) ties (the sack) on the horse"
klaar ǀʼeea ng gǃuu, a ǁʼngke haansi,
as hy klaar in die sack ingesit, maak (hom) vas op die perd"
word after /klaar/ does not really sound like /ǀʼee/, but rather like [ǁʼee]; probably a speech error again
alternative translation 'as jy klaar is da vang/maak vas jy die perd' (071120BI-03-18)
not a very grammatical clause: it should be s.th. like 'ha klaar ǀʼee ng gǃuu, a ha ǁʼngke ha ng haasi' 'when he has put (the clothes) into the bag, he tightens it (on)to the horse'
(H) "do you know what you should do?
when we go to the dune, then you do (= whip) the horse with the sjambok, so that we see (what happens then)"
a su ng ǁʼaa nǃoon, nǁae ng kxʼuu haansi nǀa sambokesi, nǀa si nǀaa",
as ons na die duin toe gaan, dan maak jy soo (maak skrik; piets) die perd met die sambok lat ons kan sien (wat sal gebeur)"
(H) "but you go and put on your clothes on the dune
"maar a ǁʼae nǁaa a ǃxaike ng nǃoon,
"maar jy loop trek jou klere op die duin aan
B and I confirm that /au/ is 'jy' here; it seems like this sentence should be continued, but it is not
[B says the context probably is: 'before you get dressed, you first must frighten the horse']
they ride, they ride, they ride, they ride, they ride, they ride, they ride, they ride, they ride, they ride
[ha ng hm] hng ǃabi, hng ǃabi, hng ǃabi, hng ǃabi, hng ǃabi, hng ǃabi, hng ǃabi, hng ǃabi, hng ǃabi, hng ǃabi,
hulle ry, hulle ry, hulle ry, hulle ry, hulle ry, hulle ry, hulle ry, hulle ry, hulle ry, hulle ry
here is the house, here is the house, here is the house, here is the house"
nǁng ke, nǁng ke, nǁng ke, nǁng ke",
hier is die huis, hier is die huis, hier is die huis, hier is die huis"
sounds like /nǁng ki a/, but B repeats /nǁng ke/ consistently; 2009: I believe now that /nǁng ke/ 'hier is die huis' is correct
context acc. to B and I: there/this is the house where the springbok girl's stay; the hare shows the house to the jackals, he say 'here is it!'
(...) "yes, I go and get dressed on the dune, I go and get dressed on the dune
[...] "ja, ǁʼae nya nǁaa nǃoon, ng ǁʼae nya nǁaa ng nǃoon,
(...) "ja, ek loop trek aan by die duin, ek loop trek aan by die duin
you don't have to tell me, I go and get dressed at the dune", (H) "yes, you shall go and get dressed at the dune, yes
"xuua (...) nya, ng ǁʼae nya nǁaa ng nǃoon", "o, a si ǁʼae nǁaa ng nǃoon, o,
moenie vir my sê nie, ek loop trek aan by die duin, "ja, jy sal loop trek aan by die duin, ja
B repeats /xuua ǀee ?(or ǂee) nya i/ 'moenie vir my sê nie'; seems to be OK, but I don't know the verb; migth be Sands 1434 /ǀkxʼee/ ''
but when we climb on the dune, then you take the sjambok and frighten your horse so that ...
hm, maar a su ǁain nǃoon, nǁae ǀai ng sambokesi, a ǀqui qain a haasi, nǀa [...]
maar as ons die duin klim, da moet jy hierdie sambok vat en die perd ('n bietjie?) skrik maak lat ...
/sau/: here repeatedly translated by I (also by B?) with 'as ons ..'
'skrik maak' => repeated by I as /kxʼuu qain/; B has /ǀqui qain/; 2009: cf. /qain/ here with /qain-ya/ 'skrik wees'
(J) "hm, I will do, I will do
"hm, ng si kxʼuu, ng si kxʼuu,
"hm, ek sal so maak, ek sal so maak
when I arrive at the dune
as ek na die duin toe kom
translated as '... as ek op die duin kom' by several speakers in several sessions, so I believe it is OK; 'as...' here because of /see/ (instead of /saa/)?
they climb the dune, he says to him
[hng si xa kua] hng ǁain nǃoon, ha ku nǁaa,
toe hulle die duin klim toe sê hy vir hom
beginning unclear, I get a different translation and repetition every time; probably speech error again
"toe klim ek af en trek an
2009: repeated with /ha/ instead of /ng/ 'hy klim af ...'
(he says do like this with the horse), then the horse bucks, then the horse bucks
[... ng kxʼuu ng] haansi, haasi nǁae oro, haasi nǁae oro,
(hy sê hy vir hom maak so (= slaan vir) die perd, toe spring die perd, toe spring die perd
beginning (everything before /haasi/) unclear; B repeats /ha ku nǁaa: kxʼuu haasi/ 'hy sê vir hom: maak (soo met) die perd'
"b" in /ǁhubu/ very weak!! its almost not there anymore
hey, what is this, the horse climbs down the dune
hey, dyisi xae, haasi ke ǁhoe nǃoon,
hey, wat is dit, (dat) die perd kom van die duin af
the little rabbit rides, he goes and chases back the horse, he comes (back)
hasietjie nǁae ǃabi, ha ǁʼae ng ǂaoke haansi, ha tsee,
toe ry haasitjie, hy loop keer die perd, hy kom
H rides after J's horse, which is running away; he chases it and he 'keers' it and brings it back
"ng tyuu xae, jy, dyisi a ke xa a ǁu ǃʼhoong, (...)
"wie is jy, hey, wat is dit (lat) jy groet nie vir uns nie

alternative translations: 'wie is jy? groet vir ons'! and 'wat is dit dat jy nie groet nie'; what are the pronouns?; 2009: again, I get a different translation and repetition for this record every time I check it
H is now among the springbok girls [SM]
oom jackal sits on the dune"
oom jakkals sit op die duin"
B repeats /gǃai/ definitely with voiced click; the vowel is quite strange on the recording, but in repetition it is [(g)ǃai] with both B and I
the jackal said he (will) come and get dressed on the dune
koro xa kua, ha sii nǁaa ng nǃoon,
jakkals het gesê hy kom trek by die duin aan
(SGs) "where is he (J)", (H) "no, I don't know where he is", (SGs) "hasn't he come" (H) "no, he hasn't come"
"[me dyee] ku dyee ku", "haʼa, ng ǁu ǁxae, ng ku dyee", "ku ǁua xa tsee", "nǃoʼe, ha ǁua xa tsee",
"waars hy, waars hy", "nee, ek weet nie waars hy", "het hy nie gekom nie", "nee, hy het nie gekom nie"
not sure if this is really a false start; B and I says, it is two times the same, /ku dyee ku, ku dyee ku/ (might be better, because normally 3SG is /ha/ and not /ku/ with B)
hm, he (H) is nou amongst/between the joung girls, amongst/between the young girls, he eats
hm, ha nǁae ǀʼii kiin ǃʼoa-ǃʼoa, ha ǀʼii kiin ǃʼoa-ǃʼoa, ha ain,
hm, hy is nou tussen die jong meide, hy eet
the second word is given alternatively as /nǁaa/ or /ǁʼaa/; is this the same?
there is another click at the beginning; part of a word or just B's meaningless(?) click at the beginning
both /ha/ '3SG sound more like [na]; check! but B repeats consistently with /ha/
he eats, he farts, he eats
ha ain, ha ǀkhuun, ha ain,
hy eet, hy poep, hy eet
B says this is NOT /ǀkoqon/ 'dance' but /ǀkhuun/ 'fart'
toe gee hulle vir hom komberse
/tsaa/ is [saa]; but when B repeats is [tsaa]
hm, then they give him blankets, they give him blankets, they give him blankets
hm, hng nǁae tsaa ha nǁaen, hng tsaa ha nǁaen, hng tsaa ha nǁaen,
hm, toe gee hulle vir hom komberse, hulle gee vir hom komberse, hulle gee vir hom komberse
hulle gee vir hom die komberse
/tsaa/ is really [tsaa], and not [saa] as in many other records from B
(they) finish to give him the blankets so that he can sleep
klaar tsaa ha nǁaen, nǀa ha ʘunn,
(toe hulle het) klaar vir hom die komberse gegee lat hy kan slaap
in the morning, he (H) stands up, (H) "hey"
in die môre, toe staan hy op "hey"
(SM) "where is the jackal?", (H) "no, he was on the dune
"koro dyee", "haʼa, [ku ke] ku xa gǃai naa nǃoon,
"waar es jakkals?", "nee, hy is (lit. staan) op die duin
I don't know where he went to"
ng ǁu ǁxae, ku xa ǁʼaea kidye",
ek weet nie waarnatoe het hy gegaan nie"
/kidye/ is [kidye(e)], also in slow repetition (ki dyee?), not /kidya/!
then he comes and meets the jackal, he sits here
ha nǁae see ng moo koro, ha tcoo ki a,
toe kom kry hy jakkals, hy sit hierso
he (H) says to the jackal "what is this, I was alone among the young girls"
ha ku ng koro, "dyisi xae, ng xa ǁʼoe ng ǀʼii tyaa ǃʼoa-ǃʼoa [ng]",
hy sê vir jakkels: "wat is dit, ek was alleen in tussen die jong meide"
H knows that the J was lying on the dune, but he wants to tease him
(H) "where have you been (so that) you didn't come?"
"gǀa xa ǁʼae kidya, ǁu xa ǁʼae",
"waar was jy dat jy nie gekom het nie?"
J says 'no, this was you' = 'this was because of you, this was your fault!'
he (H) says to him (J) "do you know this?
hy sê vir hom: "weet jy wat?
the /-a/ suffix on /ǁxae/ is sometimes there, sometimes not in repetition
you said indeed to the Boer (that) ?
a mos [ng ǃuu ku ng ǀʼhuunsi, (...)
jy het mos vir die Boer gesê ?
the first part is ignored by B and I; they also don't understand the end
die ene wat ken (= slim is)
/ǃuu ha ǁxae/ = can be translated as either 'someone who knows' or ' someone who is slim' (cf. Sands 1364 and 1365)
elicited with B: /ǃuu ha nǃunnki ǁxae/ = 'een wat baie ken' ('s.o. who is very clever')
do you see, you (that) are so very clever
sien jy, jy ken baie (= jy is slim)
H is sarcastic now, he still teases J
hierdie ding wat so baie slim is
I only hear one [a], but B always repeats /gao a a .../
[a xa] a xa ǂʼaba ǁhoe ng haasi,
jy het afgeval van die perd
do you know, have you seen
beginning could be Afrikaans (hoor maar), or /nǃoʼe, maar/ B does not really understand herself what she said
do you know this thing, I have lied ?for/behind? you for a long time
gǀa ǁxae tya (...), gao ng xa hoeka tyaa a,
weet jy (dat) ek het vir (agter) jou hoeka gelê het

word(s) between /ǁxae/ and /gao/ not clear; the first part, [dye], B and I repeat as [tya], [dya], [tye], [dye], [kye] etc; the second part [xu] is completely ignored; once it is repeated as [tyuin xoe] and [dyee ka], B's favourite is just /tya gao/

(...) sounds like [dyexu]; /tya xa/ = [dye xu]; /tyaa/ 'lie' is [dyaa]; was heißt das: 'ich habe dich herein gelegt'? oder 'ich habe dir eine Falle gestellt'? oder 'ich habe schon lange auf meine Chance gewartet'?
is /gao a/ OBJ of /ǁxae/, or VOC ('you thing = person')?!
so that I can show (it to?) you
you will get it, you will get the ?
a si moo ki, a si moo kurannsi,
jy sal hom kry, jy sal ? kry
nobody knows what [kuransi] means, I get a different translation every time I ask
do you see this ? (that) you got?
gǀa nǀai a kurannsi xa moo,
sien jy daardie ? wat jy gekry het?
uncommon appearance of /moo/ with past marker; check if it could be /maa/, or check if there is a semantic difference between /xa maa/ and /xa moo/
did you indeed think I am ?
a xa mos ǂʼainka nya, ng [...],
jy het mos gedink ek is ?
end is repeated and translated every time I ask (either 'I am a child, or 'I am the hyena'); B probably does not understand

the hyena (= Oom Piet) is very stupid; the jackal always plays tricks on him; but the hare says he is not hyena, meaning he is not so stupid that the jackal can play tricks on him; instead of this, the hare has played a trick (with the bucking horse) on the jackals this time
you have often made uncle Piet to be your "boy"
a [kxʼuua] nǃuunki kxʼuua oom Pieti ng gǀa ǀqhore,
jy het baie maal vir oom Piet die booi (hotnot) gemaak
alternative translation: 'jy het baie maal gemaak dat oom Piet jou booi is'
jackal gives hyena often instructions and he let's him work for himself (he makes hyena to be his "hotnot, booi")
you will not get this thing from me
maar a ǁala moo gaoki ng nǀng",
maar jy sal nie daardie ding kry by my nie
I have checked it, the OBL marker is definitely there
H says that J will not succeed to make H to be J's "boy"; H will not do the same stupid thing as hyena
B and I don't understand the beginning; I get a different translation every day
B repeats alternatively as [ng xa kua], [nya xa kua ...] or [na xa kua ...]
your (own) thing (= the lies that you told the Boer) will keep hold of you (= will get you in trouble now)
a se gao si ǀai ǃoo a,
first translation was 'jou ding (your lies) sal jy vashou'; alternative translation was 'jou ding sal jy loop vashou [= get in trouble]); the Nǀuu word seem to be the same for both translations
because you, you are indeed a man
want a, a mos ng ǂoo,
want jy, jy is mos 'n man
because you make us fight with the Boers
a ǀkxʼui ǀhai si ng ǀʼhuun,
want jy steek vir ons aanmekaar mit die Boere
the second verb is definitely /ǀhai/ 'kill' (confirmed by B and I); /ǀqui/ is CAUS; both parts together mean 'aanmekaar steek'; 2009: OK, checked several times now
do you see the thing you got
gǀa nǀai gao a xa maa,
sien jy die ding wat jy gekry het
you sit relaxed, you sit relaxed
a ǂxain soo, a ǂxain soo,
jy sit gerus, jy sit gerus
I have a young girl, I come hier
ng ki ǃʼoa, ng sii ng ki a
ek het 'n meisie, ek kom hier
I flirt with the springbok people
ng ǁʼng vrya ng gǃae ǂee,
ek loop vry met die springbok mense
neither B nor I understand this; B translates s.th. different every time I ask
